From Lionel Tun Subject Re Burden of Proof In article Brian Fritts writes I saw one theist on this net talking about the absurdity of one saying he doesn't believe in god and how can we be The problem with this and other arguments assumes that the burden of proof lies with the Wrong In philosophy the one who is making a positive argument must give reasons for his believing so not the If I were to make the statement elves exist then it would be up to me to prove my positive assertion not the person saying that elves don't If the negative in this case had to prove elves don't exist he would have to omniscient and know every inch of the The same applies with Give me your reasons and you the theist make the I think you have are addressing the wrong The situation is more like we both see some This is established as fact since we can both touch them Then one of us says the elves have always been with The other says no no there was a time before elves were Which is the positive argument Lionel Tun Computer Vision Group City University London ext